Uganda.adaptation:
• **CIAT & IITA** evaluated how Uganda’s policy frameworks influence gender-sensitive climate adaptation at local levels, identifying institutional gaps (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/67156**);
• **CGIAR-CCAFS** conducted household surveys in Nwoya District linking **climate-smart agricultural technologies** to reduced food insecurity and resilience (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/HPMKAW**);
• **CGIAR** mapped **power brokers** in climate policy (e.g., ACODE, Ministry of Water & Environment) to strengthen decision-making (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/21224**);
• **IFPRI** harmonized weather-variability data to measure impacts on household welfare across **agroecological zones**, informing resilience strategies (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/WP4PFG**);
• **CGIAR-CCAFS** surveyed intra-household farm decisions to scale **CSA technologies** for smallholder resilience (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/0ZEXKC**);
• **CGIAR** identified **knowledge gaps** between scientists and farmers in climate-adapted coffee systems (Mount Elgon), proposing improved information flows (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/VQUR3W**);
• **CGIAR** analyzed barriers to **climate policy implementation** in Nwoya/Rakai districts, focusing on adaptive responses (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/67896**).

coffee and cocoa.adaptation:
• **CIAT** developed **climate suitability gradients** for coffee in Central America, revealing that **33% of current production zones will become unsuitable** without adaptation, with **altitudinal shifts (200–300m upward)** required for resilience (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/93348**);
• The Center assessed **global shifts in *Coffea arabica* suitability** by 2050 using 21 climate models, informing regional adaptation strategies (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/29634**);
• **CIAT** influenced **Nicaragua’s National Adaptation Plan**, securing **$24.12M (IFAD)** and **$5.3M (Green Mountain Coffee)** for smallholder coffee/cocoa adaptation, including climate-proofed inputs and weather information systems (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/35599**);
• Researchers quantified **economic losses from inaction** in West African cocoa (Ghana/Ivory Coast), framing adaptation as a cost-effective investment to prevent farmer income declines (Sources: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/97167**, **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/100126**);
• **CIAT/Bioversity** identified **three cocoa adaptation zones in West Africa** (intensification, diversification, crop change) based on 2030s/2050s climate projections, proposing regional coordination to mitigate supply chain risks (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/1JMXC6**);
• The Center analyzed **knowledge gaps between farmers and scientists** in Uganda’s Arabica coffee systems, linking pest/disease perceptions to altitude and vegetation structure to improve climate-resilient technology adoption (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/VQUR3W**);
• **CIAT** modeled **future cocoa suitability in Ghana (2040–2069, RCP 6.0)**, supporting targeted adaptation recommendations (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/UWE6DP**);
• Researchers surveyed **348 coffee households in Honduras** to link **elevation-based resilience** to food insecurity, informing value-chain interventions (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/Z29QGA**).
